Cue the tears, friends. 😭 This is a big weight off my shoulders and an emotional relief that is hard to describe in words. Do you keep booking the wrong clients? 👀 Read on…

If you’ve been in business long enough, you’ve probably experienced some ‘trouble’ with clients before (we admit it - we have!)

Well, to paraphrase t-swift, we usually KNOW these clients are trouble when they walk in! 

The mutual qualification process is a critical stage in your clientflow for a reason! Client-business fit is key!

In our experience, bad client experiences are often predictable AND preventable.

So, if you’ve had bad client experience or 2, or 3, or more than you want to admit… (you aren’t alone!) here are a few red flag you might’ve missed:

1. Were they your most nitpicky clients those who haggled on price, compared you to competitors condescendingly, and paid the least for your products or services?

2. Did you have any gut feelings in early conversations that they may not gel well with your processes or values, but you ignored them because you needed the money?

3. During the sales process, were they consistently spotty communicators right off the bat? Did you have to repeatedly hunt them down for responses, signatures, and payments?

Now, be honest with yourself: could you sense trouble when they walked in?

Remember, it’s okay. 

It happens to the best of us. 

It’s important to take ownership and learn from past mistakes - you’ll likely come out the other side a better business owner!

What if I could give you a year of your life back? You’d likely jump at the chance. But right now, that’s the time that so many business owners are letting slip through their fingertips.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
And it breaks my heart.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Why? Because time and time again I have been reminded that the most valuable resource we have is time. To waste it, to spend even a minute of it on something that we shouldn’t be doing, is a loss that we can never get back.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
For example, let’s say that you fall down an inefficiency rabbit hole for 45 minutes five times a week. Maybe you’re manually sending over invoices instead of automating recurring payments or going back and forth on scheduling something that could have a seamlessly integrated experience… it doesn’t matter what it is.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
At first glance, losing a few minutes each day to inefficient business processes doesn’t seem like a big deal… but when multiplied across the weeks, months, and years of your entrepreneurial career — it becomes quite staggering.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Let’s do the math on that:
— 45 lost min a day, 5 times a week is 3.75 hours per week.
— 3.75 lost hours per week, 52 weeks a year is 195 hours (8.125 days) per year.
— On average, people work about 50 years over the course of their lifetime, so that’s 585,000 minutes, 9,750 hours, or 406.25 days lost over a lifetime.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Assuming clientflow issues are only costing you 3.75 hours per week, you’re losing over a year that could be spent doing anything else — going on vacations with your family, making core memories with your friends, indulging in self-care … or even maybe working on more high-impact objectives to move your brand forward.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This is why I’m so passionate about business owners leveraging the power of technology to get back more of their time. It matters.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

A few days ago, in the war against friend + family password sharing, Netflix stirred up some controversy and upset many of its customers.

What was the situation? Netflix revealed that devices would need to be logged into their “home” network every 30 days, otherwise the account would be blocked. Their help center was updated to say that a “Netflix account is for people who live together in a single household” and it coincided with external convos about how password-sharing why Netflix’s revenues aren’t higher.

This blew up on social media and led to students, frequent travelers, people in non-nuclear families, and a whole host of others outraged. The company then backtracked and said the policy update was posted on accident and would only apply to Chile, Costa Rica, and Peru.

There are so many opinions, thoughts, and PR learnings from this entire situation… however, I want to dig in to a few small business takeaways!

But first—thank you @ashleytracyphoto for jumpstarting this convo 🙌🏻🎉 & inspiring this reel.

My Takeaways:
1. Client experience is everything. Everything.
2. In business, your clients will always remember how you make them feel. (A nod to the great Maya Angelou!) If you upset them, they will make it known… often loudly… and those feelings will stick around + influence how others view your business. It’s why we read reviews!
3. Don’t immediately blame the client when things are going wrong. If revenues are down, take a look around and evaluate your business. Are you no longer offering the same value? Are you losing your competitiveness in the marketplace? Be willing to look inward before pointing blame outward.
4. Keep innovating. Even if you were once an industry disruptor—if you stop listening, iterating, and growing alongside your customers… you risk losing them.
5. Don’t overestimate the stickiness of your product or the loyalty of your customers. If you make it hard for someone to work with you, if there is friction in your clientflow, if you erode their trust (like bad communication or falling behind on deadlines)—people can and often do go elsewhere.

Share your thoughts. What does this situation show us? What can we learn?

3 Stats about Client Experience that you MUST know… 👀
 1. 86% of buyers say they would pay more for services if it’s a better experience. This is huge (especially in tough economic seasons when folks are more price sensitive). Good experiences are worth a bigger price tag… and clients value that. It’s a critical element that should not be overlooked. 

2. In their future of CX report, PwC surveyed 15,000 consumers and found that 1 in 3 customers will leave a brand they love after just one bad experience, while 92% would completely abandon a company after two or three negative interactions. 

3. What’s a bit scary though is that only 1 in 26 customers ever complains to you when they have had a bad experience… meaning that assuming no news is good news doesn’t exactly work. You need to be proactive in getting feedback and checking in on how to improve your overall clientflow.

Oh and one fun fact that I also found in my research… The most important factor in the customer experience? Fast response times. 🚨Stop ending your emails with “Let me know if you’re interested…” Try this instead.

This portion of @missellenyin’s interview on the Independent Business Podcast was gold. To improve conversion in the booking process—you need to ask guiding questions. For example, instead of ending your email with a passive statement like “let me know if you’re interested”, here are a few questions you can ask:

* Would you like to move forward with this? 
* Is this a good fit for you? 
* Which of these options do you prefer? 
* What time would you like to meet all of these?

There is power in asking questions. Science backs this up.

In 1993, social scientists Vicki Morwitz, Eric Johnson, and David Schmittlein conducted a study with more than 40,000 participants that revealed that simply asking someone, if people were going to purchase a new car within the next six months, increased the likelihood they would purchase a car by 35%. Just asking them the question. 

In an earlier study, published in the Journal of Applied Psychology, citizens were asked if they were going to vote in an upcoming election. Just by asking them if they’re going to vote, their likelihood to vote increased by 25%. 

Asking a question can change the course of your interactions with a potential client. Take this tip and run with it!

This is a hot take. I know, I know… but this single psychology theory was one of the biggest game changers for me in business—let’s talk about it! 👊🏻 

There is an old saying in sales that goes: “How do you sell a $2,000 watch? Put it next to a $10,000 watch.” This is an example of price anchoring—a cognitive bias that describes our tendency to rely too heavily on the first piece of information offered (the anchor) when making future decisions.

In other words—when we buy something we comprehend value by contrasting one price against the 'anchor' price.

When you share that your prices start at a certain number, you are anchoring your clients to that rate. Anything less than that, feels like a good deal. Anything more, feels too expensive. By anchoring at the bottom, you are positioning yourself at a disadvantage. 

Perception has a powerful influence on conversion.

By moving from ‘prices start at’ to ‘most clients spend between x and z’ for your price positioning, you are reducing the risk of clients experiencing sticker shock when you share your full array of collections or offerings. You can also round up a little to anchor prospects to a number slightly above the actual median (so when they book you, it feels even more within reach).

There is so much more to consider with price positioning—where you fall in your market, your unique business model, when in the clientflow to reveal your full pricing/offerings, even the numbers that you choose (ending in 00 communicates something very different than ending in 99 for example!) — I hope this sparks a bit of curiosity. Rooting for you.

Have you explored Threads? Yes, no, maybe? 👀 Tell me what YOU think.

Here is my early take on Threads with a small business lens:

1. If you have an existing audience on Instagram, making the jump to Threads is a smart move at this stage. There is synergy between the two and gaining traction is easier than “starting from scratch” on a brand new platform. Everyone is rediscovering folks they haven’t seen in a while on IG (thanks to the algorithm) AND it is a bit of a following frenzy as users curate their new feeds. Early-adopters, have at it.

2. Conversation is the name of the game. Meta heard our complaints about the heavy lift of video/visual on Instagram and identified a strategic moment to pounce on Twitter. Think of Threads as a casual chat and an opportunity to connect.

3. Don’t show up and start marketing. It’s not the vibe… and perhaps that is the most refreshing part about Threads at the moment. Less formality, less monetization—more humanity. (At least that is the case for now… hoping it lasts!)

4. Holy dopamine hits, Batman! 🦸‍♀️ As per usual with new social networks—the platform is giving early adopters as much dopamine as possible with high reach + engagement opportunities (paired with a notification frenzy) to create addiction. Be aware.

5. Growth is rapid (faster than my toddler running straight to the toy aisle of Target—we’re talking over 10M users in a matter of hours) — Only time will tell whether this continues and/or sustains, but this is an impressive accomplishment nonetheless.

My recommendation: if you have bandwidth this week, give Threads a try. If you don’t, remember that your business isn’t going to crumble and the world isn’t going to end (no matter what the marketing gurus say!) — Follow your gut. You’ve got this.

Six years ago, today—I went in for brain surgery in San Francisco.

And even though time continues to widen between that day and this one… I still carry the weight of that moment. I still recognize a newfound appreciation for every single day that passes.

None of this was ever a guarantee for me—least of which my two children.

The blessings in our lives aren’t guaranteed for any of us and yet often we live each day as if tomorrow is promised—so often taking for granted genuine miracles that we write off as ordinary routines on an infinite calendar.

If you take one thing away from this today… please let it be that your life is a gift. This moment, this day, is given to you with purpose and potential.

Honor your time like the gift that it is. Hug your loved ones close. Feel the air with each breath. Cherish each glimmer of joy, no matter how small.

And stop holding back… step forward boldly and with confidence.

You are here for a reason. Live today with that knowledge and let it seep deep into your bones. This world needs what only you can bring to it. So give it all that you’ve got. 💕
